Java.name: Crab
Java.template: $package   import plm.universe.turtles.Turtle;  public class Crab extends Turtle { $body  	public void run() { 		crab((Integer)getParam(0),(Double)getParam(1)); 	} }

Scala.name: Crab

Python.name: Crab
Python.correction:
# BEGIN TEMPLATE 
import math

def crab(levels, length):
		# BEGIN SOLUTION 
		if levels == 0:
			forward(length)
		else:
			left(45)
			crab(levels-1, length/math.sqrt(2))
			right(90)
			crab(levels-1, length/math.sqrt(2))
			left(45)
		# END SOLUTION	

# END TEMPLATE

crab(getParam(0), getParam(1))

initialWorlds.name: crab(0,200)
initialWorlds.about:
The universe of turtles

This is an adaptation of LOGO for the Programmer's Learning Machine.

It is directly inspired from the work of the mathematician Seymour Papert in the 60's. Inspired from the swiss psycholog Jean Piaget, he came up with a learning method called LOGO to teach programming to young childs. The world is full of turtles which leave a painting where they go and which respond to simple orders.

Functions to move the turtle

void forward(double steps)
void backward(double steps)
Moves forward or backward of the requested amount of steps. 
void right(double angle)
void left(double angle)
Turns left or right of the given angle (in degrees). 
double getX()
double getY()
Returns the current position of the turtle. Note that the point (0,0) is on the top left corner, as it is often the case in Computer Science. 
void setX(double x)
void setY(double y)
void setPos(double x, double y)
Teleports the turtle to a new position (without leaving any trace). 
void moveTo(double x, double y)
Moves the turtle to a new position. 
void circle(double radius)
Draw a circle of the specified radius centered on the turtle. 
void hide()
Hides the turtle. 
void show()
Shows the turtle back. 
boolean isVisible()
Returns whether the turtle is currently visible. 
void clear()
Removes any trail on the sheet. 
double getHeading()
Returns the current heading of the turtle (in degrees). 
void setHeading(double angle)
Sets a new heading to the turtle (in degrees).

Functions about the pen

void penUp()
Moves the pen up (turtles have pens, not brushes as buggles). The turtle will not leave any trace during its subsequent moves. 
void penDown()
Moves the pen down. The turtle will leave a trace during its subsequent moves. 
boolean isPenDown()
Returns the current pen position as a boolean. 
Color getColor()
Returns the current pen color. 
void setColor(Color color)
Changes the pen color.

Other functions

boolean isSelected()
Returns whether the current turtle is selected in the graphical interface.

Valid colors

instructions.en:
Fractal Crab

The Crab curve is not exactly a Koch curve, but that's still a fractal and it's built rather similarly. This time, we grow square triangle on the side of the figure: the angle is 45 degrees, and the length is divided by [!java|scala]Math.sqrt(2)[/!][!python]math.sqrt(2)[/!][!c]sqrt(2);[/!] at each step.

Check the figures produced by the first steps of recursion to understand the pattern.

Bibliographical note

This curve, also called the Lévy C curve was invented in 1938 by the French mathematician Paul Lévy. As usual, the wikipedia page is very instructive, and the page provide very good additions: http://www.mathcurve.com/fractals/c/c.shtml.
instructions.fr:
La fractale du crabe

La courbe du crabe n'est pas exactement une courbe de Koch, mais cette fractale est construite de façon très similaire. Cette fois, nous ne remplaçons pas le tiers central de chaque segment, mais le segment entier. À la place, il faut faire pousser des triangles isocèles et rectangles. L'angle initial est de 45°, et la longueur est divisée par [!java|scala]Math.sqrt(2)[/!][!python]math.sqrt(2)[/!][!c]sqrt(2);[/!] à chaque étape.

Vérifiez les figures produites par les premiers niveaux de récursivité pour comprendre le motif.

Note bibliographique

Cette courbe, également appelée la courbe C de Lévy, a été inventée en 1938 par le mathématicien Français Paul Lévy. Comme souvent, la page Wikipedia sur le sujet est très instructive. La page suivante apporte également des compléments intéressants : http://www.mathcurve.com/fractals/c/c.shtml.
